    "discriminators": [
     "TWO LAYERS AT ONCE, and the DUALITY is the signature: (1) a steady, quiet SPINDLE WHINE — a weak harmonic component from the platter motor (5400 rpm = 90 Hz, 7200 rpm = 120 Hz, plus pole harmonics) — underneath (2) an IRREGULAR CHATTER of head-seek clicks. A record showing BOTH a faint tonal floor AND sparse, aperiodic bright transients is a mechanical drive.",
     "Seek chatter is APERIODIC — data access is not a rhythm, it follows the file system. onset_periodicity stays LOW, which separates a drive from CMPTKey (typing has a loose but real cadence) and from any motor-driven machine (which has a hard cycle).",
     "Everything about it is QUIET: root_mean_square_level is low and it is always close-mic'd. A loud grinding version means a FAILING drive — still CMPTDriv, and the grind pushes flatness and flux up.",
     "An SSD is SILENT. If the text says SSD and the file has content, the content is something else (fan, coil whine). Coil whine in particular is an ELECBuzz-shaped harmonic comb, not a drive sound.",
     "Against MACHOffc: printers and copiers are far louder, longer, and driven by a strongly PERIODIC transport cycle."
    ],
    "confusable_with": [
