    "discriminators": [
     "AN IMPULSE TRAIN OF PLASTIC CLICKS. Typing is a sequence of very sharp, unpitched, short-decay transients at 3-8 keystrokes/second. Each keystroke is a COMPOUND event — a key-down thock plus a key-up release click — so transient_count typically runs at roughly TWICE the number of characters typed. That 2:1 structure is itself a small piece of evidence.",
     "SEMI-periodic, not periodic: human typing has cadence but not a clock's regularity. onset_periodicity ~0.2-0.5 is the sweet spot — higher than a stochastic texture like SPARKS, far lower than a machine cycle like MACHInd.",
     "Mouse CLICKS are the same object with transient_count 1-2. Mouse and trackpad MOVEMENT is near-silent friction and will often gate out of everything — expect (and accept) a low-confidence call there.",
     "Against COMType (typewriter) — the sharpest boundary available in this neighbourhood, and it is a MATERIAL-IMPEDANCE test, exactly the axis decay_time_seconds_60db exists to measure. A typewriter is METAL striking a platen: it RINGS (decay ~100-200 ms, high inharmonicity), it is loud, and it has a margin BELL. A computer keyboard is PLASTIC on plastic: it does NOT ring (decay under ~50 ms) and has no bell. DSP genuinely decides this one.",
     "Against UIClick: a synthetic UI click is band-limited and single; a keyboard is broadband, multi-transient, and has a mechanical body with a real decay."
    ],
